385
00:27:03,497 --> 00:27:08,754
<i>Then, once again, the molten rock
beneath Earth's surface burst forth...</i>

386
00:27:08,919 --> 00:27:12,139
<i>...and ﬂooded a huge area of western India.</i>

387
00:27:19,221 --> 00:27:23,567
The knockout punch
literally came out of the blue.

388
00:28:02,389 --> 00:28:04,687
Few animals larger
than a hundred pounds...

389
00:28:04,850 --> 00:28:08,070
...survived the catastrophes
of the late Cretaceous.

390
00:28:08,228 --> 00:28:11,983
The dust cloud brought night and cold
to the surface for months.

391
00:28:12,149 --> 00:28:15,369
The dinosaurs froze and starved to death.

392
00:28:15,527 --> 00:28:18,827
But there were small creatures
who took shelter in the Earth.

393
00:28:18,989 --> 00:28:20,707
<i>And when they emerged...</i>

394
00:28:20,866 --> 00:28:24,871
...they found that the monsters who had
hunted and terrorized them were gone.

395
00:28:25,037 --> 00:28:28,712
The Earth was becoming
the Planet of the Mammals.

396
00:28:29,249 --> 00:28:33,049
<i>And the Earth continued
its ceaseless changing.</i>

397
00:28:34,838 --> 00:28:37,808
This was once a desert
where nothing could grow.

398
00:28:37,966 --> 00:28:41,561
It was a million square miles
of sand and salt...

399
00:28:41,720 --> 00:28:44,974
...far more hostile
than any environment on Earth today.

400
00:28:45,140 --> 00:28:48,394
Daytime temperatures
were hot enough to bake bread.

401
00:28:48,852 --> 00:28:52,948
And it was more than a mile below sea
level, so the atmospheric pressure...

402
00:28:53,106 --> 00:28:56,280
...was about 50 percent higher
than what we're used to.

403
00:28:56,443 --> 00:29:00,243
It would be hard to think of a more
unpromising environment on this planet.

404
00:29:00,405 --> 00:29:05,332
Yet this was the basin of the Mediterranean
five and a half million years ago...

405
00:29:05,494 --> 00:29:07,792
...before it became a sea.

406
00:29:07,955 --> 00:29:10,504
The Earth never stops moving for long.

407
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:15,379
<i>The natural dam at the western end
of the deep basin gave way...</i>

408
00:29:15,545 --> 00:29:17,513
<i>...probably due to earthquakes.</i>

409
00:29:17,673 --> 00:29:20,176
<i>And the deluge began.</i>

410
00:29:21,009 --> 00:29:26,061
The torrential waters rushed in at a rate
40,000 times greater than Niagara Falls...

411
00:29:26,223 --> 00:29:32,731
...turning a vast desert into the
Mediterranean Sea in less than a year.

412
00:29:34,648 --> 00:29:37,948
There were as yet no humans
to witness this enormous flood...

413
00:29:38,110 --> 00:29:41,034
...nor to admire the beauty it created.

414
00:29:41,196 --> 00:29:43,164
Meanwhile, half a world away...

415
00:29:43,323 --> 00:29:47,123
<i>...a broad channel
separated North and South America...</i>

416
00:29:47,286 --> 00:29:51,757
<i>...allowing ocean currents to ﬂow
from the Atlantic into the Pacific Ocean.</i>

417
00:29:51,915 --> 00:29:55,510
<i>Tectonic forces gradually brought
these two continents together...</i>

418
00:29:55,669 --> 00:30:00,015
<i>...closing the channel
and creating the Isthmus of Panama.</i>

419
00:30:00,173 --> 00:30:03,473
This reorganized the worldwide pattern
of ocean currents...

420
00:30:03,635 --> 00:30:06,058
...which, in turn, affected
the global climate.

421
00:30:09,433 --> 00:30:15,361
<i>In Africa, the lush green forest canopy
gave way to a sparser landscape.</i>

422
00:30:15,522 --> 00:30:20,574
<i>Some species that were highly specialized
for life in the trees became extinct.</i>

423
00:30:20,736 --> 00:30:23,990
<i>But the generalists, the ones
that could find a way to make a living...</i>

424
00:30:24,156 --> 00:30:28,536
<i>...no matter what life threw at them,
endured and evolved.</i>

425
00:30:31,747 --> 00:30:34,421
<i>Our ancestors had once burrowed deep
in the ground...</i>

426
00:30:34,583 --> 00:30:37,883
<i>...to avoid predators who
stalked the surface.</i>

427
00:30:38,045 --> 00:30:41,595
But when the dinosaurs perished,
they emerged into the daylight...

428
00:30:41,757 --> 00:30:45,557
...and over the eons, made new lives
in the branches of the trees.

429
00:30:45,719 --> 00:30:49,599
<i>They developed opposable thumbs and toes
for swinging from branch to branch...</i>

430
00:30:49,765 --> 00:30:53,941
<i>...across the broad canopy of treetops,
where all their needs were fulfilled.</i>

431
00:30:54,102 --> 00:30:57,732
They could also walk upright,
but only for short distances.

432
00:30:57,898 --> 00:31:01,448
<i>With so many trees around,
they didn't have to go very far.</i>

433
00:31:01,610 --> 00:31:05,035
<i>But then it got colder,
and the trees thinned out.</i>

434
00:31:05,197 --> 00:31:07,245
<i>Broad grasslands sprang up...</i>

435
00:31:07,407 --> 00:31:10,877
<i>...and our ancestors were forced
